'''Manjumori Kofun''' (万寿森古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kofu|ja|甲府市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamanashi Prefecture|ja|山梨県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Yumura. It has been Historic Site1 as a Yamanashi Prefecture Historic Site<ref>{{PDFlink|[https://www.pref.yamanashi.jp/gyousei-kk/kouhou/documents/2582.pdf Yamanashi Prefecture Official Gazette No. 2582]}}</ref>.

== location and Geographic-Historical Landscape ==

The tumulus is situated at the northern edge of the {{ill|Kofu Basin|ja|甲府盆地|12=draft|12=draft}}, on the southern foothills of {{ill|Mount Yumura|ja|湯村山|12=draft|12=draft}}, at an elevation of approximately 300 meters<ref name="#1">* {{Cite book|title=Yamanashi Prefecture Place names|publisher=Heibonsha|year=1995|page=357}}</ref>. 

The surrounding area, including Yumura, Chizuka, Haguro, and Yamamiya neighborhoods, is known for the {{ill|Chizuka-Yamamiya Kofun Cluster|ja|千塚・山宮古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}}, which features a high concentration of Kofuns<ref name="#1"/>. Notable sites include the Enokida ruins in Chizuka, which span from the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft|12=draft}} to the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, and feature remains such as {{ill|burial Practices of the Yayoi built|lt=rectangular moat tombs|ja|方形周溝墓|12=draft|12=draft}} from the Yayoi period<ref>Yamanashi Prefecture Place names, p.355</ref>.

Nearby kofun include the {{ill|Kamuna Kofun|ja|加牟那塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, built in the late 6th century and the second largest tumulus in Yamanashi Prefecture, and the {{ill|Otengu-san Kofun|ja|おてんぐさん古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, a 6th-century stone-piled circular mound. These sites are part of the broader landscape associated with immigrant burial traditions<ref name="#2">Tashiro and Hagiwara (1984), p.48</ref>.

The Manjumori Kofun is one of several mounds in the Yumura Mountain cluster, many of which have been lost to modern development<ref name="#2"/>.

== burial and built ==

[[File:Manjumori ancient Kofun in 1910 's.jpg|thumb|250px|Manjumori Kofun, circa early Taisho period.]]
[[File:Manjumori Kofun, genshitsu-1.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Main Chamber (玄室)}}]]

The tumulus measures 31 meters east-west, 38 meters north-south, and 5 meters in height<ref name="#1"/>. The burial facility is a south-facing {{ill|corridor-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}} constructed with andesite fieldstones<ref name="#1"/>. The chamber features "random stone stacking" (小口積み・横口積み) with smaller stones (50-80 cm)<ref name="#1"/>.

The chamber is 14.2 meters long, with a main chamber (玄室) measuring 7.9 meters and a passage (羨道) of 5.3 meters<ref name="#1"/>. Chamber width varies, being 2.44 meters near the rear wall and narrowing to 1.55 meters at the entrance<ref name="#1"/>. The chamber height reaches a maximum of 3.3 meters but is partially obscured by later concrete paving<ref name="#1"/>.

Although no burial goods, haniwa, or surrounding facilities have been found, comparisons with nearby kofun suggest an earlier construction date relative to the large stone-built mounds in the region<ref name="#1"/>.

The tumulus has been known since the Edo period and was repurposed as a storage facility for gunpowder (煙硝蔵). In modern times, it served as a hotel warehouse, with the addition of doors and concrete flooring<ref name="#1"/>.

