Nearby kofun include the {{ill|Kamunazuka Kofun|lt=Kamunazuka Kofun|lt=Kamuna Kofun|ja|加牟那塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamuna Kofun|qq=}}, built in the late 6th century and the second largest tumulus in Yamanashi Prefecture, and the {{ill|Mount Tengu|lt=Mount Tengu|lt=Otengu-san Kofun|ja|おてんぐさん古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otengu-san Kofun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天狗山 (甲府市)}}, a 6th-century stone-piled circular mound. These sites are part of the broader landscape associated with immigrant burial traditions<ref name="#2">Tashiro and Hagiwara (1984), p.48</ref>.

The Manjumori Kofun is one of several mounds in the Yumura Mountain cluster, many of which have been lost to modern development<ref name="#2"/>.

== burial and built ==

[[File:Manjumori ancient Kofun in 1910 's.jpg|thumb|250px|Manjumori Kofun, circa early Taisho period.]]
[[File:Manjumori Kofun, genshitsu-1.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Main Chamber (玄室)}}]]

The tumulus measures 31 meters east-west, 38 meters north-south, and 5 meters in height<ref name="#1"/>. The burial facility is a south-facing {{ill|corridor-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/corridor-style stone chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} constructed with andesite fieldstones<ref name="#1"/>. The chamber features "random stone stacking" (小口積み・横口積み) with smaller stones (50-80 cm)<ref name="#1"/>.

The chamber is 14.2 meters long, with a main chamber (玄室) measuring 7.9 meters and a passage (羨道) of 5.3 meters<ref name="#1"/>. Chamber width varies, being 2.44 meters near the rear wall and narrowing to 1.55 meters at the entrance<ref name="#1"/>. The chamber height reaches a maximum of 3.3 meters but is partially obscured by later concrete paving<ref name="#1"/>.

Although no burial goods, haniwa, or surrounding facilities have been found, comparisons with nearby kofun suggest an earlier construction date relative to the large stone-built mounds in the region<ref name="#1"/>.

The tumulus has been known since the Edo period and was repurposed as a storage facility for gunpowder (煙硝蔵). In modern times, it served as a hotel warehouse, with the addition of doors and concrete flooring<ref name="#1"/>.

